Aranict	A Letherii human mage holding the rank of Atri-Ceda in the Letherii Army. Tall and in her late thirties, with sun-faded brown hair worn loose and deep mouth creases from a lifetime of rustleaf, she appears not yet fully accustomed to military rank. Previously employed as a midwife in Trate, she is strongest in healing magic but possesses potential for other sorceries as well.<br>
Asane	A Letherii exile wandering in the Wastelands. She is one of the displaced Letherii far from settled imperial life, part of a small group moving through harsh and uncertain terrain.<br>
Badalle	A human child and one of the leaders of the Snake. She writes sad poetry that reflects the hardship endured by herself and the children travelling with her. Her works include Pendulums Were Once Toys and Of a River, giving her a distinct voice of witness and sorrow within the Snake's desperate journey.<br>
Bakal	A warrior of the Senan clan of the White Face Barghast. His identity is rooted in the martial culture of the Barghast clans, among whom clan belonging and warrior status define social place and reputation.<br>
Bavedict	A Letherii alchemist fascinated by Moranth munitions and associated with the New Bridgeburners. Thin-lipped, with hair worn in a long braid that he coils atop his head with grease, he once kept a profitable shop in Letheras. He travels with a large black-varnished carriage fitted with brass and drawn by four black horses, giving him the air of a practical but eccentric specialist.<br>
Brayderal	A tall, bony girl with an unusually white face who appears near the head of the Snake after its march has begun. She is one of the children of the Snake, where stark physical impressions and sudden appearances carry weight in a desperate travelling community.<br>
Bre'nigan	A J'an Sentinel belonging to Matron Gunth'an Acyl. At least a thousand years old, tall, and gaunt, he has murky yellow eyes misshapen with cataracts, with neither pupils nor irises visible. Though possibly blind, he moves with perfect sureness, grace, and liquid elegance, giving him an ancient and uncanny poise.<br>
Brolos Haran	One of three Bonecasters of the Orshayn T'lan Imass, alongside Ilm Absinos and Ulag Togtil. Broadly built even in undeath, with unusually large bones beneath tight, dried-out skin, he bears remnants of red hair and a brownish-grey emlava fur across his shoulders. His shrunken black eyes, copper-coloured teeth, stern manner, and gloomy nature give him a severe ancient presence.<br>
Fast	A Bonehunters captain originally from Li Heng. His captaincy is a field promotion, and Ruthan Gudd regards him as ambitious and upwardly mobile. Pinch-faced and professionally advancing, he represents one of the newer command figures within the Malazan army's shifting officer corps.<br>
Gu'Rull	A K'Chain Che'Malle Shi'Gal Assassin of immense age, serving Matron Gunth'an Acyl. His long service includes victories over other Shi'Gal, and his Matron has altered his body beyond the usual form of his kind. Feather-scaled wings like those of a middle-aged Eleint and an extra set of eyes beneath his jaw allow him to look downward even in flight, making him a highly specialised aerial killer.<br>
Gunth'an Acyl	Matron of the K'Chain Che'Malle nest Acyl. Her sole daughter is Gunth Mach. As a Matron, she occupies one of the central generative and commanding roles within K'Chain Che'Malle society, shaping both her nest and the specialised servants who act in her name.<br>
Hanavat	Wife of Warleader Gall of the Khundryl Burned Tears. When pregnant, she is sometimes addressed by the honorific Mahib. Her position ties her directly to Khundryl leadership, household continuity, and the cultural respect given to motherhood among the Burned Tears.<br>
Held	A baby girl who is part of the Snake. She is named by Rutt, the boy who carries her, and her presence among the travelling children gives the Snake one of its most vulnerable and symbolically weighty figures.<br>
Ilm Absinos	An Orshayn T'lan Imass Bonecaster. She is clothed in enkar'al scales, carries a serpent staff, and wears long black hair knotted with snake-skins. A hip injury gives her a hitched gait, adding to her distinctive, reptilian-shamanic presence among the Orshayn.<br>
Inistral Ovan	A T'lan Imass and Warleader of the Orshayn. The available source gives only this sparse identification, placing him as a martial leader among that Imass group without further safe descriptive detail.<br>
Jarabb	Tear Runner to Warleader Gall of the Khundryl Burned Tears. He has thick fingers and wears a helmet over a padded doeskin cap. His closeness to Gall suggests a personal as well as formal bond, placing him near the centre of Burned Tears leadership and command.<br>
Kalt Urmanal	An Orshayn T'lan Imass. The available source provides only this sparse identification, placing the character among the ancient Imass associated with the Orshayn group.<br>
Kalyth|Elan	An Elan woman serving as Destriant to the K'Chain Che'Malle. Her role places her in a rare and unsettling spiritual relationship with an elder non-human people, marking her as a human religious figure tied to powers far outside ordinary mortal society.<br>
Kisswhere	A Dal Honese sapper in Sergeant Sinter's 4th Squad, 8th Legion, 3rd Company of the Bonehunters, and Sinter's sister. Onyx-skinned and socially magnetic, she has a skill for seducing men and attracts both infatuation and unwanted attention within the army. She joins the Malazan military on a whim, seeking escape from Dal Hon's drudgery, only to find desertion less simple once her sister follows her into service.<br>
Kor Thuran	A K'Chain Che'Malle K'ell Hunter and one of the guardians of Destriant Kalyth, alongside Sag'Churok and Rythok. The page gives little more, but his role identifies him as one of the formidable martial protectors attached to the K'Chain Che'Malle's chosen human Destriant.<br>
Krughava	A Perish woman, Mortal Sword of the Grey Helms, sworn to Fanderay and Togg, the Wolves of Winter. Huge and broad-shouldered, with fair skin, iron-hued hair, blazing blue eyes, scar-seamed weathered features, and a stern angular face, she appears carved from the raw cliffs of Perish. Her physical strength is matched by formidable will, and she is famed among the order for mastery across many weapons. She wears blackened chain and carries a blue-iron longsword with a silver wolf's-head pommel.<br>
Last	A Letherii exile wandering in the Wastelands. The available source gives only this sparse identification, placing the character among displaced Letherii travelling through harsh country beyond settled imperial life.<br>
Lera Epar	A T'lan Imass Bonecaster of the Brold whose name means Bitterspring. Once beautiful, she was regarded as a formidable seer, though she understood her foresight as rooted in a keen grasp of human nature rather than simple prophecy. Her reputation among her kin combined awe, desire, resentment, and reverence.<br>
Maral Eb	Warchief of the Barahn clan of the White Face Barghast. He wears bronze brigandine armour, greases his spiky hair with red-tipped porcupine quills, and marks his white war-mask and arms with red ochre. Fierce and ambitious, he imagines himself at the point of a barbed spearhead when the Barahn are on the move. His brothers Sagal and Kashat are capable young warriors tied to his ambitions.<br>
Nappet	A Letherii exile wandering in the Wastelands. He had previously been sentenced to hard labour quarrying in the Bluerose mountains after a violent family dispute, giving him a rough background among those driven out into exile and deprivation.<br>
Nom Kala	A female Bonecaster of the Brold T'lan Imass. Her name means Knife Drip in the Imass language. The available source gives little safe non-plot detail beyond her identity, gender, people, and Bonecaster role.<br>
Nose Stream	A Bonehunters sergeant in Hedge's squad of New Bridgeburners. Recruited from Letheras, he receives his new name from Master Sergeant Pores, placing him among the Letherii recruits folded into Malazan military naming customs and squad life.<br>
Pinosel	A resident of Letheras and sometime lover of Ursto Hoobutt. He calls her Cherrytart, while she calls him a fat, flea-bit oaf. Both are described as ugly, though she has bright diamond-like eyes and crow's-nest hair, giving her a sharp, comic presence among Letheras's rougher common folk.<br>
Raband	A Napan lieutenant serving under Captain Ruthan Gudd in the Bonehunters. Sullen in manner and difficult to read, she strikes Gudd as possibly incompetent or potentially murderous, making her a subordinate whose silence carries an edge of uncertainty.<br>
Roach	A rare Hengese lapdog owned by the Malazan noble Lenestro in Sialk. Long-haired, with a ratty tail, mangy ears, and a pug nose, she is walked on a jewel-studded leash. Scruffy, pampered, and memorable, she stands out as one of the few named animals in the dramatis personae.<br>
Rumjugs	A corporal in Hedge's squad of New Bridgeburners. Recruited from a brothel in Letheras alongside Sweetlard, she is an enormous, sweaty woman with black hair, small eyes, and full lips. Her background and physical presence make her one of the rougher Letherii recruits absorbed into the Malazan military orbit.<br>
Run'Thurvian	Destriant of the Perish Grey Helms, sworn to Fanderay and Togg, the Wolves of Winter. Tall, gaunt, bald, and fair-skinned, he wears a heavy dark-grey woollen robe and speaks fluent Malazan. His role places him as one of the Grey Helms' sacred triad, alongside their Mortal Sword and Shield Anvil.<br>
Rutt	A young boy and one of the leaders of the Snake. Tall and painfully thin, with protruding shoulders, elbows, knees, and ankles, slack stretched skin, large luminous eyes, and all his teeth, he carries the baby Held. His physical fragility and responsibility give him a central, protective role among the children.<br>
Rystalle Ev	One of the Orshayn T'lan Imass. The available source provides only this sparse identification, placing the character among the ancient Imass associated with the Orshayn group.<br>
Rythok	A K'Chain Che'Malle K'ell Hunter and one of the guardians of Destriant Kalyth, alongside Sag'Churok and Kor Thuran. The page gives little more, but his role identifies him as one of the martial protectors attached to the K'Chain Che'Malle's chosen human Destriant.<br>
Saddic	One of the children of the Snake and a follower of Rutt. He reveres Badalle, commits her poems to memory, and says he is collecting them for her. He also gathers small things such as shiny stones and crystal shards, carrying them with him in a bag.<br>
Setoc of the Wolves	A name associated with Stayandi, a young Letherii girl from Drene also known as Setoc. The exact page for this title is absent, but the allowed source identifies Setoc as her pseudonym. Kept here in the form used by the source character list, the entry is limited to the safe identity connection and avoids future or traumatic details.<br>
Sheb	A Letherii exile wandering in the Wastelands. The available source gives only this sparse identification, placing the character among displaced Letherii travelling through harsh country beyond settled imperial life.<br>
Shelemasa	A member of the Khundryl Burned Tears. The available source gives only this sparse identification, placing her among the Khundryl people associated with Warleader Gall and his clan.<br>
Sinter	A Dal Honese sergeant commanding the 4th Squad, 8th Legion, 3rd Company of the Bonehunters. From the southern jungles of Dal Hon and the same tribe as Badan Gruk, she joins the Malazan army to follow and protect her beloved sister Kisswhere. Practical and watchful, she is tied to several strong emotional currents within her squad, including Badan Gruk's affection for her and Pravalak Rim's infatuation with her sister.<br>
Skanarow	A Bonehunters captain of Kanese origin. Uncharacteristically tall and lean-limbed for a Kanese woman, with black hair, scar-seamed harsh features, and a surprisingly lovely smile, she has a face Ruthan Gudd compares to someone suckled among wildcats. Her name is archaic Kanese for a female hill-dog, and her sayings suggest descent from fishing folk.<br>
Skincut Ralata	A seasoned warrior of the Skincuts, an all-female subgroup of the Ahkrata clan of the White Face Barghast. Well-muscled, with long reddish hair worn braided, she dresses in distinctly barbaric garb and armour made from Moranth chitin, including a rare Gold Moranth chest-piece. Like others of the Ahkrata, she wears broad hollow nose plugs.<br>
Stavi	Daughter of Hetan and Kruppe, with a twin sister named Storii and a younger half-brother named Absi from Hetan's relationship with Onos T'oolan. Of mixed Barghast and human heritage, she belongs to a small family web connecting the White Face Barghast to Darujhistan's most singular little man.<br>
Stolmen	Warchief of the Gadra clan of the White Face Barghast. Huge, stolid, broad-shouldered, and scarred, he tends to lumber when he walks and wears a bhederin cloak. When armoured, he carries a twin-bladed axe and heavy hook-knife. Easily influenced by his wife Sekara and slow to grasp fast-moving events, he has the heavy presence of a powerful but limited clan leader.<br>
Storii	Daughter of Hetan and Kruppe, with a twin sister named Stavi and a younger half-brother named Absi from Hetan's relationship with Onos T'oolan. Of mixed Barghast and human heritage, she shares the same unusual family ties linking Barghast blood, Daru eccentricity, and the household around Hetan.<br>
Strahl	A warrior of the Senan clan of the White Face Barghast. The page contains little safe non-plot detail beyond his clan and warrior status, which place him within the martial society of the Senan Barghast.<br>
Sulkit	A K'Chain Che'Malle drone found within Kalse Rooted. No taller than an adult human male, it is thin-limbed, with a mass of tentacles instead of fingers, a broad head bulging behind the eyes and at the base of the skull, a lizard-like mouth lined with multiple rows of fine sharp fangs, and oversized soft-brown eyes.<br>
Sunrise	A former Letherii craftsman and member of Hedge's New Bridgeburners. Scrawny and about forty years old in appearance, with a huge stained moustache, he represents one of the Letherii recruits drawn into the rough, improvised company forming around Hedge.<br>
Sweetlard	A corporal in Hedge's squad of New Bridgeburners. Recruited from a brothel in Letheras alongside Rumjugs, she is an enormous, sweaty blonde woman with small eyes. Her background and physical presence make her one of the more memorable Letherii recruits absorbed into Hedge's company.<br>
Tanakalian	Young Shield Anvil of the Perish Grey Helms, sworn to Fanderay and Togg, the Wolves of Winter. Fair-skinned and broad-shouldered, with wheat-yellow hair and deep grey eyes, he wears the blackened chain, grey cloak, and distinctive iron helmet of the Grey Helms. His role places him in the order's sacred triad beside its Mortal Sword and Destriant.<br>
The Errant|Errastas	An Elder God also known as Errastas, worshipped by Letherii and by enclaves of Imass, Barghast, and Trell. Regarded as a mysterious purveyor of chance, fateful circumstance, and ill-chosen impulses, he is Master of the Holds or Tiles, an older counterpart to the Master of the Deck. Patterns are his obsession, and he considers his mastery of them beyond challenge.<br>
Ulag Togtil	A Bonecaster of the Orshayn T'lan Imass. An Imass-Trell half-breed, he has long been an outsider among the Orshayn clans, having lived among early Trell tribes before coming among the Imass. He is regarded as the most formidable of the Orshayn Bonecasters in wars against the Order of the Red Sash.<br>
Untilly Rum	A field-promoted Bonehunters captain commanding light lancers. A former marine, he is described by Ruthan Gudd as an island-bred ferret of a man, yet he can ride like a Wickan. His position marks a shift from marine service into mounted command within the Malazan army.<br>
Ursto Hoobutt	A resident of Letheras and sometime lover of Pinosel. He calls her Cherrytart, while she calls him a fat, flea-bit oaf. Both are described as ugly, and he has gnarled hands, giving him a coarse comic presence among the common Letherii figures surrounding Tehol's city.<br>
Vedith	An officer of Gall's Khundryl Burned Tears. The available source gives little safe non-plot detail beyond his position, placing him within the leadership structure of the Khundryl clan under Gall.<br>
